\par\plain {\f1\fs20\b0\i0 The Faust of early books \endash  as well as the ballads, dramas, movies, and puppet-plays which grew out of them \endash  is irrevocably damned because he prefers human knowledge over divine knowledge: "He laid the\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holy_Scriptures"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs20\b0\i0 Holy Scriptures}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 \~behind the door and under the bench, refused to be called\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_of_theology"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs20\b0\i0 doctor of theology}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 , but preferred to be styled\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_of_medicine"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs20\b0\i0 doctor of medicine}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 ".}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faust#cite_note-2"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs20\b0\i0\super [2]}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 \~Chapbooks containing variants of this legend were popular throughout Germany in the 16th century. The story was popularised in England by\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Marlowe"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs20\b0\i0 Christopher Marlowe}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 , who gave it a classic treatment in his play\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Faustus_(play)"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs20\b0\i1 The Tragical History of Doctor Faustus}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 \~(c. 1592).}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faust#cite_note-3"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs20\b0\i0\super [3]}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 \~In\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goethe%27s_Faust"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs20\b0\i0 Goethe's reworking of the story}}{\f1\fs20\b0\i0 \~over two hundred years later, Faust seduces a pious girl who then dies by suicide, but after many further adventures Faust is saved from damnation through the intervention of penitent women, including the girl whose life he ruined.}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  }
